Japan, China, India, Thailand, South Korea: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview

-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 
2011-07-07T22:17:03Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-07/japan-china-india-thailand-south-korea-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Edano will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in  Tokyo .  The May current-account balance probably shrank to 306
billion yen ($3.8 billion) from 405.6 billion yen in April,
according to a Bloomberg News survey of economists before the
Ministry of Finance releases the data at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo.  The yield on the 1.2 percent government bond due June 2021
was 1.17 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker. The yen traded at
81.23 per dollar at 6:53 a.m. in Tokyo.  China : The government will sell 15 billion yuan ($2.3
billion) of 182-day bills today and  China Development Bank  will
offer 15 billion yuan of 10-year notes.  The yield on the government’s 3.99 percent notes due June
2021 was 3.91 percent. The yuan was at 6.4658 per dollar.  India : The country will sell a combined 120 billion rupees
($2.7 billion) of bonds maturing in 2017, 2022, and 2027.  The yield on the 7.80 percent bonds due April 2021 was 8.36
percent. The rupee was at 44.440 per dollar.  South Korea : The government will report the producer price
index for June today. The gauge dropped to 6.2 percent the
previous month, the lowest level since February.  The yield on the 4.25 percent bonds due June 2021 was 4.3
percent. The won was at 1,064.05 per dollar.  Taiwan: The central bank will sell NT$100 billion ($3.5
billion) of 364-day bills.  The yield on the 1.375 percent bonds due March 2021 was
1.48 percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The Taiwan
dollar was at NT$28.860 per dollar.  Thailand: The government will report foreign reserves as of
July 1. The holdings were $184.3 billion previously.  The central bank will sell 50 billion baht ($1.6 billion)
of 14-day bills.  The yield on the 5.40 percent bond due July 2016 was 3.99
percent. The baht was at 30.35 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Andrea Wong in  Hong Kong  at 
